[1]
Date: Sun 2 Dec 2018
Source: The Sun [edited]
https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/7879109/global-std-crisis-as-incurable-super-gonorrhoea-syphilis-and-chlamydia-hit-record-high/


Rates of sexually transmitted diseases like syphilis, chlamydia and "incurable" super gonorrhoea are reaching record highs, a shock report reveals. Millions of new infections have been recorded over the past 4 years alone in the USA, health chiefs have said. A drug-resistant strain of gonorrhoea is on the rise as sexually transmitted disease (STD) cases rocket worldwide.

It comes after it emerged cases of syphilis reported in England have reached the highest level since 1949 -- up almost 150% in 10 years. There has also been a worrying spike in gonorrhoea and the emergence of so-called super gonorrhoea -- which is drug resistant. And the latest report from the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) suggests it is a worldwide trend (see reference below).

There were almost 2.3 million Americans with chlamydia, gonorrhoea and syphilis last year [2017], up from 1.7 million in 2013, the CDC revealed. Their report, released in September [2018], said chlamydia was most common in women, whereas gonorrhoea and syphilis were more common in men. Syphilis infected almost 8 men to every woman, according to the findings. Teens aged 15 to 19 and adults aged 20 to 29 are the groups at highest risk of infection in the USA. And surprisingly, rates of gonorrhoea and chlamydia were among their highest in the typically conservative "Bible belt" areas of the South. Syphilis was most common in Nevada, California and Louisiana.

In the UK, public health officials warned of the spread of drug-resistant gonorrhoea -- thought to have been carried from Southeast Asia earlier this year [2018]. Commenting on the drug-resistant strain, the CDC said symptoms include a burning sensation while urinating and a green or yellow discharge.

A statement from the CDC said: "The emergence of cephalosporin-resistant gonorrhoea would significantly complicate the ability of providers to treat gonorrhoea successfully, since we have few antibiotic options left that are simple, well-studied, well-tolerated and highly effective."

There were 422 000 new STD cases in 2017, according to a Public Health England report earlier this year [2018]. Of these, there were 7137 diagnoses of syphilis -- a 20% increase compared with 2016 and a 148% increase from 2008. Cases of gonorrhoea were up 22% from 2016, while the number of chlamydia cases dropped 8%.

Those most at risk of infections were young heterosexuals aged 15 to 24, black ethnic minorities, and gay or bisexual men.

Meanwhile in Australia, STD cases increased by 107% and gonorrhoea increased by 63% between 2011 and 2016, CNN reported.

[Byline: Neal Baker]

