[2]
Date: Thu 6 Dec 2018
Source: Project Q Atlanta [edited]
http://www.projectq.us/atlanta/Syphilis_infections_soar_among_gay_bisexual_men


New cases of syphilis have skyrocketed nationwide in the past 5 years, and gay and bisexual men are responsible for nearly 70% of new infections, according to a recent report from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

"I am not surprised," said Quintin Robinson , an infectious diseases doctor at Atlanta-based AbsoluteCARE. "I see at least 2 to 3 cases of syphilis in my practice per week, primarily among gay and bisexual men living with HIV."

The CDC report [https://www.cdc.gov/nchhstp/newsroom/2018/press-release-2018-std-prevention-conference.html] showed that syphilis diagnoses increased 76% between 2013 and 2017. Gonorrhea diagnoses increased 67% (nearly doubling among men) in the same period.

What's driving the uptick in syphilis and gonorrhea cases is due to many factors, Robinson said. But he pushed back against an argument from critics of PrEP that the daily preventative measure against HIV leads gay men to engage in risky sex, and causes an increase in sexually transmitted infections (STIs). "The STI rates were increasing among gay/bisexual and other MSM [men who have sex with men] long before the rapidly growing uptake in PrEP, but the increase in STIs is due to many things," Robinson said.

He said that more routine STI testing -- PrEP users are screened for STIs every 90 days -- and the increase in condom-less sex are factors. But so is treatment as prevention, which is treating people living with HIV to lower the risk of new HIV transmissions by taking antiretroviral medication. The concept of "undetectable equals untransmittable" is also a factor, Robinson said. The CDC said [https://www.hivplusmag.com/undetectable/2017/9/27/breaking-cdc-officially-recognizes-undetectableuntransmittable-hiv-prevention] in 2017 that when antiretroviral treatment results in viral suppression in those living with HIV, that prevents [HIV] transmission to others. So when it comes to these increases in STI rates, Robinson said not to blame PrEP. "It's reductionist and unproductive to blame PrEP, as it effectively prevents HIV, which is a big deal," he said.

A 2016 CDC report [http://www.projectq.us/atlanta/gay_male_syphilis_rate_40_times_higher_than_others?gid=18025] showed that the rate of syphilis among gay and bisexual men was at least 40 times the rate of heterosexual men.

[Byline: Patrick Saunders]

